Text.Value: Yes, well, enough time spent in violent captivity at the hands of brutal thugs will do that to a man.
Are you selling these forgeries?
My stardom has waned somewhat recently, but I was once feted as one of the city's most promising artists.
I'll take a look.
Of course not! It's absolutely real - I painted it myself.
No thanks to you.
Well, I'm not giving them away.
You.
You're fortunate I've work to do, or I'd show you exactly where they like to stick a palette knife.
These days my oeuvre is less original, shall we say, but no less in demand.
Aha. Then perhaps you'd be interested in taking a look at my stock. I've a rather special piece that's become unexpectedly available.
It's a shame, but then the curse of true originality was always to be undervalued.
I've a rather wonderful painting that's become unexpectedly available.
My name is Oskar Fevras, though I doubt you'll have heard it.
I think it's going rather well. I've more gold in my pockets now than I ever had begging for Lady Jannath's scraps.
My good friend, do you know where you are? The Guildhall is no place for the morally squeamish.
I assure you, it's identical to the original down to the finest brush stroke. A fine piece to hang on the wall of anyone you decide to sell it to.
Oh, I never asked. Why bother, when I'm finally an artist of independent means?
Hardly the line of work I expected to end up in, but I can say one thing for them - they understand the value of art.
So you're a criminal.
Now if you'll excuse me, I've got orders to fulfil, and this Kalain won't forge itself.
Who are 'they'?
I'd like to trade.
If people can't tell the difference between my work and the original, then who's to say it is any less precious than the real thing?
In fact, you're fortunate to have caught me just now. I've a rather special piece that's become unexpectedly available.
Ah. We had a very interested party out in Waterdeep who, shall we say, commissioned the piece. But when the time came, she was unable to pay.
You left me in that bloody Zhentarim camp to rot.
You're working for the Zhentarim?
Oh - and a word of advice. Don't try to sell it down here - I've already tried, and they aren't interested.
Ouch. I didn't take you for the violent type.
Well, culture isn't for everyone. Perhaps gold is of more value to you, yes?
Who are you?
Of course. There's nothing like art to soothe a troubled soul.
Why did it become available?
Go on. Tell me where.
I only have one painting available. Though, of course, I will have to charge you extra. For being an utter bastard.
Hmm. You look rather more refined than the usual thugs walking these halls. I don't suppose you have any interest in fine art?
Oh, wonderful. Back again, are we?

EditorData.NodeContext: Super pissed off - you abandoned him with violent thugs. Low voice - doesn't want to be overheard

Text.Value: Why not just return to your patron?
Oh, and if you're thinking about selling that to anyone down here - forget it. They aren't as stupid as they look. Or as friendly.
You'll find out for yourself if you get on the wrong side of them. The Zhentarim aren't much for subtlety.
The Zhentarim, of course. I've learned a trick or two from them since you abandoned me in their filthy encampment.
Fortunately, the Zhentarim stopped threatening to break my fingers when they realised it would be bad for business.
So it's a counterfeit.
Glad you made it out.
It is simply derived from an existing source of inspiration.
I convinced them that a true artist cannot perform in captivity, and so we agreed to proceed on a mutually beneficial basis.
They do, however, know the work of a master when they see it.
I'm more interested in the purses required to buy such pieces.
Leave.
Then perhaps I might be able to interest you in a rather special piece I've just completed. It's become unexpectedly available.
What are you doing in the Guildhall?
I've no time for such distractions.
Making a living, of course.
I hear parts of her have washed up as far away as Neverwinter.
They are very reasonable people. I produce the work, and they handle the distribution.
As such, this piece is destined for the cooking fire, unless you'd like to take it off my hands?
Not interested.
Aha. Well, I wouldn't put it in quite those terms. I'm simply a duplicator of artistic works that already exist.
After you failed to rescue me from their encampment, the Zhentarim and I settled our differences, so to speak.
Changed your mind?
Sounds rather unethical.
If, however, you're open to the idea of supporting the arts, then we may do some fine business.
What have you got?

Synopsis: Oskar is in the Guildhall, working as a counterfeiter with the Zhentarim. If the player met him previously and refused/failed to help him, he's quite angry at them, but has nonetheless managed to create a more comfortable situation for himself. If the player never met him, he's simply a counterfeiter trying to sell them a fake painting he needs to offload.
